The paper proposes a new architecture for generative adversarial networks (GANs) that can learn hierarchically interpretable representations without relying on detailed supervision. This involves incorporating a decision tree latent controller (DTLC) into the generator input, which has a multiple-layer tree structure. The paper also proposes a hierarchical conditional mutual information regularization and a curriculum learning method to optimize the DTLC-GAN. The paper evaluates the DTLC-GAN on various datasets and applies it to image-retrieval tasks. Based on this, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also involves some natural language processing (NLP) techniques, which could place it in cs.CL (Computation and Language). Finally, the use of decision trees and hierarchical structures could also suggest cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
